3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates based on the difference between perpetual and oracle prices, with rates updated every hour. The platform uses Chainlink oracles for price discovery, eliminating traditional order book mechanics. Funding payments flow between long and short positions through the GLP pool, with the pool acting as the counterparty. Higher trading fees (0.05%-0.07%) compared to CEXs are offset by the protocol's decentralized nature and oracle-based execution."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ETHFI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETHFI's role as an Ethereum restaking protocol token creates unique funding dynamics tied to ETH staking yields and DeFi adoption cycles. The smaller trading volume on GMX compared to major CEXs can lead to funding rate premiums during periods of asymmetric positioning. Oracle dependency provides more stable pricing but can create arbitrage opportunities when CEX prices diverge significantly from oracle feeds."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETHFI funding rates on GMX typically range from -0.01% to 0.05% per hour, with higher volatility during major Ethereum network upgrades or restaking protocol announcements. The oracle-based system tends to produce more stable rates compared to order book exchanges, but can lag during rapid market movements. Funding rates often correlate with ETH staking yield changes and broader DeFi sector sentiment. Weekend periods frequently show reduced volatility due to lower institutional activity in DeFi markets."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage opportunities arise when GMX funding rates deviate significantly from Binance or OKX rates, particularly during high volatility periods. The 1-hour funding interval provides more frequent arbitrage windows compared to 8-hour systems on CEXs. Oracle lag during rapid price movements can create temporary mispricings suitable for delta-neutral strategies. GLP pool mechanics mean that large position imbalances can persist longer than on traditional exchanges, extending profitable arbitrage periods."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency creates smart contract risk and potential for price feed manipulation, though Chainlink's reputation mitigates this concern. Higher trading fees on GMX (0.05%-0.07%) can erode arbitrage profits on smaller position sizes compared to CEX alternatives. Arbitrum network congestion during high activity periods may delay position adjustments and funding collections. The relatively small ETHFI trading volume means larger positions can experience significant price impact, affecting the viability of substantial arbitrage operations."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does GMX's oracle-based funding differ from traditional CEX systems for ETHFI?","answer":"GMX uses Chainlink oracles for price discovery rather than order books, creating more stable but potentially lagged funding rates. This system reduces manipulation risk but can create arbitrage opportunities when oracle prices diverge from CEX spot prices during volatile periods."},{"question":"What makes ETHFI funding rates unique on decentralized exchanges?","answer":"ETHFI's connection to Ethereum restaking creates funding patterns tied to ETH staking yields and DeFi adoption cycles. On DEXs like GMX, these fundamentals often drive longer-term funding trends compared to the more speculative short-term movements seen on centralized exchanges."},{"question":"How do GLP pool mechanics affect ETHFI funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"GLP pools act as counterparties to all trades, meaning position imbalances can persist longer than traditional exchanges. This creates extended periods of favorable funding rates but also increases counterparty risk through the pool mechanism rather than direct peer-to-peer matching."},{"question":"What are the main risks of funding rate arbitrage on GMX vs centralized exchanges?","answer":"GMX carries smart contract risk, oracle dependency, and higher trading fees that can erode profits. However, it offers resistance to traditional exchange manipulation and provides access to DeFi yield opportunities that aren't available on centralized platforms."}]}]
